'''Cheli''', according to the [[Real Academia Española|Royal Spanish Academy]], is the jargon with elements of certain traditional working class districts of [[Madrid]], [[Spain]], such as [[Lavapiés]] and [[Atocha (Arganzuela)|Atocha]] in the southern part of the old city (close to [[cockney]] culture of [[London]]'s [[East End of London|East End]]), together with marginal and counter-cultural elements.<ref>Diccionario de la Real Academia de la Lengua, http://www.rae.es/rae.html</ref>

Cheli, mainly a juvenile jargon, especially strong in the early 1980s, is linked to the movement called ''[[La Movida Madrileña|movida]]'' in [[Madrid]]. It is still used by some people and despite its limited semantic fields, related to marginality, parties, drugs, nightlife and friendship, several words have been accepted by the [[Real Academia Española|Royal Spanish Academy]], due to its wide expansion.

