{{About||the 1938 German film|The Four Companions (film)}} {{unreferenced section|date=October 2013}} {{Shia Islam|Beliefs and practices}} '''The Four Companions''', also called '''the Four Pillars of the Sahaba''' is a [[Shi'a|Shiʿah]] term for the four [[Sahaba]] who stayed most loyal to [[Imam Ali]] after the death of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]]: * [[Abu Dhar al-Ghifari|Abū Dharr al-Ghifāri]] * [[Ammar ibn Yasir|Ammār ibn Yāsir]] * [[Miqdad ibn Aswad|al-Miqdad ibn Aswād al-Kindi]] * [[Salman the Persian|Salman al-Fārsī]]
Those among [[sahaba|Muhammad's companions]] who were closest to both [[Muhammad]] and [[Imam Ali]] were called [[Shia etymology|Shiʿah of Ali]] "partisans of Ali" during Muhammad's lifetime, and it was for these primarily that the following hadith was said:{{quote|Glad tidings, [[Ali]]! Verily you and your Shiʿah will be in Paradise.}} These companions are later referred to as "The Real Shiʿah". [[Abd Allah ibn Abbas|Abdullah ibn Abbas]], [[Muhammad ibn Abi Bakr]] and [[Malik al-Ashtar]] were other such partisans. However, it is only The Four Companions that are believed to have attained the rank of "The Real Shiʿah" and remained so.
